y mining evolved. The tunnellers constructed hundreds of deep dugouts that housed tens of thousands of troops. Often electrically lit and ventilated, these tunnels incorporated headquarters, cookhouses, soup kitchens, hospitals, drying rooms, and workshops. A few dugouts survive today, a final physical legacy of the Great War, and are presented for the first time in photographs in Beneath Flanders Fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aTunnelingzBelgiumxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xCampaignszBelgium. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xEngineering and construction. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xTunnel warfarezBelgium. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh1 aDoyle, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aVandewalle, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357311640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773573116423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773573116/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles